ðŸ’¡ What Is a Log File?

A log file records what happens in your system or application.
Examples:

/var/log/syslog â†’ system messages

/var/log/nginx/error.log â†’ web server logs

/var/log/messages â†’ general Linux logs

ðŸ§­ What You Want to Do

ðŸ‘‰ Check if any error or fail message is found in a log file.

If yes â†’ show a message or send an alert.
If not â†’ say â€œNo errors foundâ€.

ðŸ§¾ Simple Script to Check Logs

=====================================================================================================================================================================

#!/bin/bash
# Script Name : check_logs.sh
# Purpose     : To check if any errors are found in log file

# 1. Path of the log file
LOG_FILE="/var/log/syslog"

# 2. Keywords to search for
KEYWORDS="error|fail|critical"

# 3. Check last 100 lines for keywords
tail -n 100 $LOG_FILE | grep -iE "$KEYWORDS" > /tmp/error_logs.txt

# 4. If errors found, show message
if [ -s /tmp/error_logs.txt ]; then
    echo "âš ï¸  Errors found in $LOG_FILE"
    cat /tmp/error_logs.txt
else
    echo "âœ… No errors found in $LOG_FILE"
fi
=================================================================================================================================================================================================

ðŸ§  Step-by-Step Explanation
Line	What it does
LOG_FILE="/var/log/syslog"	Select which log file to check.
`KEYWORDS="error	fail
tail -n 100	Looks at the last 100 lines (recent logs).
grep -iE	Searches for the keywords (case-insensitive).
> /tmp/error_logs.txt	Saves output to a temporary file.
if [ -s file ]	Checks if the file is not empty (means errors found).
cat /tmp/error_logs.txt	Displays the found errors.
